–1384","1311–Female":"1311–Afdød","1327":"1327","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","about 1326":"omkring 1326","1384":"1384","about 1311":"omkring 1311","Abt 1327":"omkring 1327","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1311–":"circa 1311–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1327–1384":"1327–1384","1311–Female":"1311–Overleden","1327":"1327","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","about 1326":"circa 1326","1384":"1384","about 1311":"circa 1311","Abt 1327":"circa 1327","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1311–":"about 1311–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1327–1384":"1327–1384","1311–Female":"1311–Deceased","1327":"1327","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","about 1326":"about 1326","1384":"1384","about 1311":"about 1311","Abt 1327":"about 1327","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret was born about 1311, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Mauger Vavasour about 1326, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1311–":"umbes 1311–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1327–1384":"1327–1384","1311–Female":"1311–Surnud","1327":"1327","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","about 1326":"umbes 1326","1384":"1384","about 1311":"umbes 1311","Abt 132